        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>These are continuum observations, so the lowest spectral resolution is adequate.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>An angular resolution of 1 arcsecond is more than sufficient to accomplish our science aims.  We have set the band center so that the CO line falls within baseband 4, to allow us to attempt to measure the nuclear star formation rate.  For these science goals a single, 22 minute snapshot is sufficient.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The primary science goal is detection of the decaying TDE, which is expected to have a flux of approximately 13.6 mJy (+/- 20% depending on the date of observation; see Scientific Justification).  Proper modeling of the spectral energy distribution at any epoch requires both a flux and a spectral index.  We would like to measure spectral index to +/- 0.1, an accuracy comparable to the systematic error in the radio-mm slope estimate. As the ALMA basebands span roughly 10% in frequency, if we assume a worst-case scenario where the object is a factor 3 below the model predictions, we need an RMS of approximately 40 uJy in two images -- one for basebands 1 &amp; 2, the other for basebands 3 &amp; 4.  This yields a final RMS of 28 uJy per beam for all 4 basebands combined, the number used in the OT.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The frequencies have been chosen to include the CO line in baseband 4.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_NON_STD_CONT_FREQ</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
    </prj:ScienceGoal>
