    <prp:abstract>We propose an ALMA follow-up observation of the nearest tidal disruption event (TDE) in NGC 4845 (d=17 Mpc).  This event, detected initially by Integral in the X-rays and later by JVLA in the radio, is believed to be due to the disruption of a super-Jupiter by the central supermassive black hole of this galaxy.  Its closeness offers us a so far unique close-up of the disruption process and its aftermath. The ALMA follow-up will enable us to dissect the late-stage evolution of the emission from the TDE, allowing for a criticla test of the jet launching and propatating model.  Combining the mm observation with complementary radio and X-ray data will further allow us to determine the time-dependent broadband spectral energy distribution, and hence probe the electron acceleration due to the jet-medium interaction.  The ALMA spectroscopic imaging will also map out the continuum and/or line emissions around the nucleus, tracing past galactic nuclear activities.</prp:abstract>
